---
import ServiceLayout from '../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';
import heroImage from '../assets/images/wp-import/burgess-exam.jpg';
---

<ServiceLayout
  heroImage={heroImage}
  title="Emergency & Urgent Veterinary Care in Lake in the Hills, IL | Healthy Paws Animal Hospital"
  description="Urgent veterinary care in Lake in the Hills, IL during business hours — we make every effort to see urgent cases the same day. For after-hours and true emergencies, we refer to our trusted emergency partners. Call (815) 322-5400."
  serviceName="Emergency & Urgent Care"
  serviceDescription="During business hours we make every effort to see urgent cases the same day (a same-day fee applies). For after-hours care and true emergencies, we refer to our trusted local emergency partners."
  faqs={[
    {
      question: 'Does Healthy Paws handle emergencies?',
      answer: 'During our regular business hours, we make every effort to help when your pet has an urgent or emergency problem — call us right away at (815) 322-5400 and we will do our best to see your pet the same day (a same-day urgent care fee applies). If we are unable to accommodate the case, or if it is a true emergency that needs round-the-clock critical care, we will recommend one of the emergency hospitals on our Specialty & Emergency Partners page.',
    },
    {
      question: 'What about after-hours emergencies?',
      answer: 'We are not a 24-hour hospital, so for emergencies outside our business hours please go directly to one of the emergency centers listed on our Specialty & Emergency Partners page. Several are open 24/7. If you are unsure, you can call us first — our voicemail also points you to emergency referral information.',
    },
    {
      question: 'What are your business hours?',
      answer: 'Monday and Tuesday 7:00 AM–6:00 PM, Wednesday 8:00 AM–6:00 PM, Thursday 10:00 AM–6:00 PM, and Friday 7:00 AM–5:00 PM. We are closed Saturday and Sunday. Urgent cases are seen during these hours whenever we are able.',
    },
    {
      question: 'How do I know if my pet needs emergency care?',
      answer: 'Signs that need immediate attention include difficulty breathing, uncontrolled bleeding, inability to urinate, seizures, collapse, suspected poisoning, severe vomiting or diarrhea (especially with blood), trauma such as being hit by a car, and sudden inability to walk. When in doubt, call us — we would always rather hear from you and help you decide than have you wait when your pet needs care.',
    },
    {
      question: 'Should I call before bringing my pet in?',
      answer: 'Yes, please call (815) 322-5400 before heading over. Calling ahead lets our team prepare for your pet\'s arrival, give first-aid guidance over the phone, and let you know right away whether we can see your pet that day or whether you should head straight to an emergency partner.',
    },
  ]}
  relatedServices={['surgery', 'laboratory-diagnostics', 'specialty-partners']}
>
  <h2>When Your Pet Needs Urgent Attention</h2>
  <p>
    When your pet is sick or injured and can't wait for a scheduled appointment, we are here to help. During our regular business hours, we make every effort to assist with urgent and emergency situations and to see your pet the same day whenever we are able (a same-day urgent care fee applies). <strong>If your pet needs urgent help, call us right away at <a href="tel:+18153225400">(815) 322-5400</a>.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Healthy Paws is a full-service general practice, not a 24-hour emergency hospital. If we are unable to accommodate your pet, or if the situation is a true emergency that needs round-the-clock critical care, we will recommend one of our trusted emergency partners. For anything outside our business hours, please head directly to one of those emergency centers.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-8 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-hpah-green bg-hpah-green-light p-6">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">After Hours or a True Emergency?</h3>
    <p class="mb-4 text-hpah-text">
      We refer after-hours and critical cases to a network of local 24/7 emergency and specialty hospitals — including poison control contacts. Find the nearest one, with addresses and phone numbers, on our partners page.
    </p>
    <a href="/specialty-partners/" class="btn-primary">View Specialty &amp; Emergency Partners</a>
  </div>

  <h2>What Constitutes a Veterinary Emergency?</h2>
  <p>
    Some situations need immediate veterinary attention. Call us (during business hours) or go straight to an <a href="/specialty-partners/">emergency partner</a> if you observe any of the following:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Breathing difficulty</strong> — labored breathing, choking, or blue-tinged gums</li>
    <li><strong>Trauma</strong> — hit by car, falls from height, or animal attacks</li>
    <li><strong>Uncontrolled bleeding</strong> — wounds that won't stop bleeding with direct pressure</li>
    <li><strong>Inability to urinate</strong> — straining to urinate with no output (especially in male cats)</li>
    <li><strong>Seizures</strong> — especially first-time seizures or clusters of seizures</li>
    <li><strong>Suspected poisoning</strong> — ingestion of toxic foods, chemicals, plants, or medications</li>
    <li><strong>Collapse or sudden weakness</strong> — inability to stand or sudden loss of consciousness</li>
    <li><strong>Severe vomiting or diarrhea</strong> — particularly with blood, or in very young or senior pets</li>
    <li><strong>Bloated or distended abdomen</strong> — especially in large-breed dogs with nonproductive retching</li>
    <li><strong>Eye injuries</strong> — sudden swelling, discharge, squinting, or visible trauma to the eye</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Do</h2>

  <h3>During Business Hours</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Call us at <a href="tel:+18153225400">(815) 322-5400</a></strong> — We'll assess the situation, give guidance, and let you know whether we can see your pet the same day or whether you should head straight to an emergency partner.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep your pet calm and safe</strong> — Minimize movement if you suspect a broken bone or spinal injury. Wrap your pet gently in a towel or blanket for transport.</li>
    <li><strong>Do not give any medications</strong> — unless specifically instructed by our team.</li>
    <li><strong>Drive safely</strong> — If we're expecting you, focus on getting here safely.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>After Hours or When We Can't Accommodate</h3>
  <p>
    For emergencies outside our business hours — or any time we're unable to take an urgent case — go directly to one of the 24-hour hospitals on our <a href="/specialty-partners/">Specialty &amp; Emergency Partners</a> page. For suspected poisoning, that page also lists the Pet Poison Helpline and ASPCA Poison Control. If you're unsure whether something can wait until morning, err on the side of caution and seek emergency care.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Can Do During Business Hours</h2>
  <p>
    When we're able to see your pet for an urgent visit, depending on the situation our team can provide:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Triage and stabilization</li>
    <li><a href="/laboratory-diagnostics/">In-house laboratory diagnostics</a> for fast results</li>
    <li>Digital radiography</li>
    <li>Fluid therapy and supportive care</li>
    <li><a href="/pain-management/">Pain management</a></li>
    <li>Wound care and bandaging</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Cases that need round-the-clock monitoring, overnight hospitalization, or critical/specialty care are referred to one of our <a href="/specialty-partners/">emergency partners</a>, where a team is available 24/7.
  </p>

  <h2>Urgent vs. Emergency: What's the Difference?</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Emergencies</strong> are life-threatening situations that need immediate intervention — these often need a 24-hour facility. <strong>Urgent care</strong> covers conditions that need same-day attention but may not be immediately life-threatening — things like sudden limping, ear infections causing severe discomfort, eye irritation, persistent vomiting, or acute allergic reactions.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you're unsure which category your pet's situation falls into, call us. We'll help you determine the right level of care and, if you need an emergency hospital, point you to the nearest one.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
